<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The people sang freedom songs and accused ward 54 Councillor Morgan Tshaka of nepotism.Community leader Simphiwe Dayimani told Daily Sun: “Most of the residents protesting today are poor. “We decided to stop the school renovation because we are not happy about how the councillor is treating us.” Dayimani claimed Tshaka broke their job creation agreement.“We agreed with him that a community project must prioritise employment and be shared among the poor people in our ward.“But we found he employed his friends and relatives. “We were also annoyed by the number of people coming from other wards and from Wells Estate who were employed on this project.” Concerned resident Lona Bessong (45) confirmed she was removed from the list of small businesses supposed to get work.She told Daily Sun: “This project started at the end of last year.“ I followed all the requirements and attended all the site meetings.“I was placed in fifth position on the list of small businesses. “But when my turn arrived to start working, the councillor fired me. “He told me I did not qualify.“This is sad because there are no other jobs available.”But Tshaka had a different view.He told Daily Sun: “This is not a service delivery complaint. “These people are just provoking me personally. “They always intimidate me in my efforts to provide service delivery. “They approached me in the wrong manner and I am unable to attend to their grievances,” said the councillor.